Read images from files and display the images¶

This notebook covers three different ways of reading images from a file.
You will need to do this when you want to compare an image to some of the images files
which contain categories e.g., (CIFAR-10, CIFAR-100 and other data sets:
https://www.tensorflow.org/datasets/catalog/overview) for image classification (CNN) models.

Python Modules:
1. OpenCV
2. Pillow
3. MatplotLib

There are also other ways:
Python's scikit (load_sample_image)
Tensorflow:

Method 1: Use Opencv-python¶

OpenCV (Open Source Computer Vision Library: http://opencv.org) is an open-source BSD-licensed library that includes
several hundreds of computer vision algorithms.
It allows you to modify pixels in place.

OpenCV Functionality includes:
Image/video I/O, processing, display (core, imgproc, highgui)
Object/feature detection (objdetect, features2d, nonfree)
Geometry-based monocular or stereo computer vision (calib3d, stitching, videostab)
Computational photography (photo, video, superres)
Machine learning & clustering (ml, flann)
CUDA acceleration (gpu)
https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/opencv-overview/

Why are colors different? OpenCV uses BGR as its default colour order for images, matplotlib uses RGB. When you display an image loaded with OpenCv in matplotlib the channels will be back to front.

The easiest way of fixing this is to use OpenCV to explicitly convert it back to RGB.

In [8]:
img = cv2.imread('grumpycat1.jpg')
#RGB_img = cv2.cvtColor(img,cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
# The following will create a gray image
GRAY_img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)

# Display image using matplotlib
#plt.imshow(RGB_img, interpolation = 'bicubic')
plt.imshow(GRAY_img, interpolation = 'bicubic')
plt.xticks([]), plt.yticks([])  # to hide tick values on X and Y axis
plt.show()

Obtain size of an image using OpenCV¶

Obtain dimensions of image using .shape

Height represents the number of pixel rows in the image or the number of pixels in each column of the image array.

Width represents the number of pixel columns in the image or the number of pixels in each row of the image array.

Number of Channels represents the number of components used to represent each pixel.

In [9]:
dimensions = img.shape 
height = img.shape[0]   # Height is at index 0  
width = img.shape[1]    # Width is at index 1   
channels = img.shape[2] # no. of channels is at index 2

print('Image Dimension    : ',dimensions)
print('Image Width        : ',width)
print('Image Height       : ',height)
print('Number of Channels : ',channels)

Image Dimension    :  (1501, 1801, 3)
Image Width        :  1801
Image Height       :  1501
Number of Channels :  3

Method 2: Use Pillow¶

Use Image.open
Note: Opens and identifies the given image file.

This is a lazy operation; this function identifies the file, but the file remains open and the actual image data is NOT read from the file until you try to process the data (or call the load() method). See new().

Use of %matplotlib inline
Tells IPython where (and how) to display plots
With this backend, the output of plotting commands is displayed inline within frontends like the Jupyter notebook, directly below the code cell that produced it. The resulting plots will then also be stored in the notebook document.

Convert image to grayscale
Use image.covert()
When translating a color image to greyscale (mode “L”), the library uses the ITU-R 601-2 luma transform:
L = R 299/1000 + G 587/1000 + B * 114/1000
The default method of converting a greyscale (“L”) or “RGB” image into a bilevel (mode “1”) image uses Floyd-Steinberg dither to approximate the original image luminosity levels. If dither is NONE, all values larger than 128 are set to 255 (white), all other values to 0 (black).
https://pillow.readthedocs.io/en/stable/reference/Image.html

In [21]:
g_img = img1.convert('L')
g_img.show()

Create a thumbnail from the original file
Use image.thumbnail
Create a thumbnail from the original file (grumpycat1.jpg). Note: Function modifies the Image object in place. Image.thumbnail resizes to the largest size that (a) preserves the aspect ratio, (b) does not exceed the original image, and (c) does not exceed the size specified in the arguments of thumbnail. Also image.thumbnail preserves the aspect ratio. https://stackoverflow.com/questions/29367990/what-is-the-difference-between-image-resize-and-image-thumbnail-in-pillow-python

Method 3: Use Matplotlib¶

For RGB and RGBA images, matplotlib supports float32 and uint8 data types. For grayscale, matplotlib supports only float32 If your array data does not meet one of these descriptions, you need to rescale it.
imshow() is the most common way to display images in Matplotlib.

Set up Imports

In [27]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.image as mpimg

Use matplotlib.image.imread(fname, format=None)
Read an image from a file into an array.

In [28]:
img=mpimg.imread(r'grumpycat1.jpg')

Does Matplotlib work with pixels in images?¶

Note: Matplotlib does not work with pixels directly but rather physical sizes and Dots per Inch (DPI). If you want to display a figure with a certain pixel size, you need to know the DPI of your monitor. This link will detect that for you: https://www.infobyip.com/detectmonitordpi.php
My monitor DPI:
132 x 132

Dots per Inches (dpi) determines how many pixels the figure comprises.

Figure size (figsize) determines the size of the figure in inches. This gives the amount of space the axes (and other elements) have inside the figure. The default figure size is (6.4, 4.8) inches in matplotlib 2. A larger figure size will allow for longer texts, more axes or more ticklabels to be shown.
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/13714454/specifying-and-saving-a-figure-with-exact-size-in-pixels https://stackoverflow.com/questions/47633546/relationship-between-dpi-and-figure-size

In [29]:
fig = plt.figure()
size = fig.get_size_inches()*fig.dpi # size in pixels

<Figure size 640x480 with 0 Axes>

Note: The imread() function is used to read image data in an ndarray object of float32 dtype.
https://www.tutorialspoint.com/matplotlib/matplotlib_working_with_images.htm
